The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Wednesday, March 31, 2004  Business Briefs																								 New Delhi, March 30: The new pension scheme for government employees, scheduled to start in April, will be delayed as the appointment of fund managers is being deferred till July. The expectations are that the pension fund managers will be appointed within three to four months, said U. K. Sinha, joint secretary (pension and capital markets). He said the mutual fund would have to compete with the pension sector.																								 Mumbai, March 30: Pfizer Ltd has reported a 55.38 per cent rise in net profit to Rs 12.26 crore for the first quarter ended February 29 compared with Rs 7.89 crore posted in the same period last year. Total income also increased to Rs 137.35 crore as against Rs 108.35 crore posted in the corresponding previous quarter.																								 Calcutta, March 30: Essar Shipping Ltd today said it has fully redeemed non-convertible debentures of Rs 78.54 crore ($17.82 million) that were subscribed by Unit Trust of India.																								 Mumbai, March 30: Export Credit Guarantee Corporation of India Ltd is working out a sustainable model to provide a loss cover to exporters in lieu of the recent steep appreciation of the rupee against the dollar causing concern to the export community.																								 New Delhi, March 30: The government has increased by 13.5 per cent the gross margin target for Indian Oil Corporation (IOC) in the new memorandum of understanding for 2004-05, signed by chairman M. S. Ramachandran and petroleum secretary B. K. Chaturvedi.																								 New Delhi, March 30: A rise in bus and truck sales of Tata Motors and Ashok Leyland pushed commercial vehicle sales up by a robust 35.7 per cent in the first 11 months of this fiscal, according to the Society of Indian Automobile Manufacturers.																								 New Delhi, March 30: Specialised information security manpower will become a major requirement for the Indian IT sector with the demand for such professionals projected to rise to 77,000 in 2008 from 18,000 at present, Nasscom said.
